  "signature": "ed25519:b7d3a9c2f1e04b8d6a5c3f2e9b1d7a4c8f0e2b5d9a3c6f1e8b4d0a7c2f5e9b3d1",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Version-controlled solver with documented change logs, regression test suite covering hemolysis-relevant flow regimes, and traceable build environment for all production runs.",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (OpenFOAM v9, branch hemolysis-vad) is maintained under Git version control with tagged releases. A regression suite of 47 test cases covering turbulent pipe flow, rotating frame, and shear-thinning fluid benchmarks was executed against the tagged release with zero failures. Build environment is containerized (Docker image SHA recorded) ensuring full reproducibility. SQA audit completed by independent reviewer on 2025-11-14. Required level 4 met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Method of manufactured solutions (MMS) or equivalent order-of-accuracy test demonstrating correct spatial and temporal discretization for the governing equations used in the hemolysis model.",
      "rationale": "Method of manufactured solutions was applied to the incompressible Navier-Stokes solver with rotating frame source terms. Observed spatial order of accuracy was 1.94 (theoretical: 2.0) on a sequence of four uniformly refined grids. Temporal order of accuracy was 1.97 for the second-order implicit scheme. Hemolysis transport scalar equation verified separately with MMS; observed order 1.96. All results within accepted tolerance of theoretical order. Required level 3 met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Richardson extrapolation-based grid convergence index (GCI) reported for hemolysis index QoI at all five operating points; GCI < 5% on fine grid for each point.",
      "rationale": "Grid triplet (coarse: 4.2M cells, medium: 11.8M cells, fine: 31.4M cells) was run at all five VAD operating conditions. Richardson extrapolation performed per Celik et al. (2008). GCI on fine grid ranged from 1.1% to 3.8% across operating points for the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH). Oscillatory convergence was not observed. Asymptotic range ratios were within [0.95, 1.05] for four of five points; the fifth (5 L/min, 3600 RPM) yielded a ratio of 1.07, flagged in the uncertainty budget but not exceeding acceptance threshold. Required level 4 met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions (fluid properties, rotational speed, flow rates, temperature) documented with measurement uncertainty; conditions match CFD boundary conditions within stated tolerances.",
      "rationale": "FDA generic pump bench tests were conducted using a bovine blood analog (35% glycerol in PBS) with viscosity measured at test temperature (37 ± 0.5 °C). Flow rate controlled via Coriolis meter (±0.5% FS), rotational speed via encoder (±2 RPM). All five operating points replicated in CFD with boundary conditions set to measured mean values. Fluid property uncertainty propagated through CFD via Latin hypercube sampling (n=200). Test condition documentation archived in study record TR-2025-VAD-001. Required level 3 met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative validation metric (e.g., E% or NRMSE) reported for NIH at all operating points with experimental uncertainty intervals; CFD predictions within combined simulation and experimental uncertainty at ≥4 of 5 points.",
      "rationale": "Normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) compared at five operating points. Experimental uncertainty (95% CI) ranged from ±8% to ±14% of measured NIH. CFD prediction intervals (Monte Carlo, 95%) ranged from ±11% to ±19%. Overlap between intervals confirmed at all five points. E% ranged from 3.2% to 12.7%; NRMSE = 0.089. The largest discrepancy (12.7% at 6 L/min, 2800 RPM) was within the combined uncertainty band. Validation metric formally satisfies required level 4."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs used in validation (NIH, shear stress distribution) are the same quantities used in the COU decision; no surrogate or proxy quantities substituted without justification.",
      "rationale": "The primary COU QoI is absolute NIH for regulatory comparison against the clinical threshold (NIH < 0.01 g/100 L). Validation activities directly measure and predict NIH using the same power-law hemolysis model applied in the COU. Shear stress distributions are reported as secondary QoIs and are consistent between validation and COU geometries. No surrogate quantities were used. Required level 3 met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation cases cover the full COU operating envelope (flow rates 3–7 L/min, speeds 2400–3800 RPM); geometry, fluid, and boundary conditions are representative of the VAD COU.",
      "rationale": "Validation was performed on the FDA generic centrifugal pump — the same geometry family as the COU device. Five operating points span the clinical operating envelope (3.5–6.5 L/min, 2600–3800 RPM). Blood analog fluid properties are representative of human blood at physiological hematocrit. Rotating frame, inlet/outlet boundary conditions, and wall boundary treatment are identical between validation and COU simulations. Validation activity relevance is assessed as high; required level 4 met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence demonstrated to at least 4 orders of magnitude reduction in residuals for all transport equations; mass imbalance < 0.01% of inlet mass flow.",
      "rationale": "All simulations run to 5-order residual reduction for continuity, momentum, and hemolysis scalar. Mass imbalance monitored at each time step; maximum observed imbalance was 0.004% of inlet mass flow across all five operating points. Convergence plots archived for each run. Required level 3 met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation setup reviewed by a second qualified analyst; checklist-based review of boundary conditions, material properties, solver settings, and post-processing scripts completed and documented.",
      "rationale": "Independent peer review of simulation setup performed by a second CFD analyst with VAD hemolysis experience. Review checklist (18 items) completed with no deficiencies identified. Boundary condition input files, material property tables, and post-processing scripts archived under version control and reviewed. Required level 3 met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The hemolysis power-law model form and turbulence closure are validated against independent experimental datasets beyond the primary FDA pump data, with sensitivity analysis demonstrating that model form uncertainty is bounded and acceptable relative to the clinical decision threshold.",
      "rationale": "The power-law hemolysis model (Giersiepen et al. coefficients, modified by Heuser and Opitz) has been applied in over 40 published VAD hemolysis studies and is widely accepted within the field as the standard formulation for NIH prediction in centrifugal pumps. The k-ω SST turbulence closure was selected based on its established performance in rotating machinery applications and has been validated in three prior pump geometries by the assessment team over the past six years. Sensitivity analysis was performed by varying the power-law exponents (α, β) within their published uncertainty ranges (±15%) using a one-at-a-time approach; the resulting NIH variation was ±22% of the nominal prediction, which the team judged acceptable given the 2× safety margin between predicted NIH and the clinical threshold. Expert judgment from two senior hemolysis modelers (combined 30+ years experience) was obtained and documented, both concurring that the model form is appropriate for this COU. While a full multi-model ensemble comparison against an independent dataset (e.g., the Bludszuweit dataset or a second pump geometry) was not completed within the project timeline, the breadth of prior literature application and the conservative safety margin provide substantial indirect confidence that model form error will not lead to an incorrect accept/reject decision. The team therefore considers the model form credibility to be functionally adequate for the intended regulatory submission, even though the formal evidence package does not include the independent cross-geometry validation dataset that would formally satisfy level 4.",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/model-form-vad-cou2"
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All model inputs (geometry, fluid properties, operating conditions) characterized with uncertainty; uncertainty propagated to QoI via Monte Carlo or equivalent method.",
      "rationale": "Geometry uncertainty quantified via laser scan comparison (±0.05 mm surface deviation). Fluid viscosity, density, and power-law hemolysis coefficients sampled from literature-derived distributions. Monte Carlo propagation (n=500 LHS samples) performed; 95% prediction interval on NIH reported at all operating points. Required level 3 met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "At least three independent experimental replicates per operating point; blood analog batch-to-batch variability characterized.",
      "rationale": "Five independent experimental replicates were performed at each of the five operating points (n=25 total runs). Blood analog was prepared from three separate glycerol-PBS batches; batch-to-batch viscosity variation was < 2.1%. Inter-replicate coefficient of variation on NIH ranged from 4.3% to 9.7%. Required level 3 met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Dimensionless similarity parameters (Reynolds number, flow coefficient, head coefficient) match between validation experiments and COU operating conditions within ±10%.",
      "rationale": "Reynolds numbers at all five operating points match between validation (FDA generic pump) and COU (Class III VAD) within 6.3%. Flow coefficient (Q/ND³) and head coefficient (ΔP/ρN²D²) match within 4.1% and 7.8% respectively. Equivalency confirmed via dimensional analysis table in TR-2025-VAD-001, Section 5.3. Required level 3 met."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/vad-cou2-credibility-decision-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-review-panel",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Following comprehensive review of all 13 credibility factors, the assessment panel concludes that the CFD hemolysis model is sufficiently credible for use in the Class III VAD regulatory submission context. Twelve of thirteen factors achieved their required credibility levels. The single exception — Model form (achievedLevel 3, requiredLevel 4) — was reviewed in detail by the panel. The panel notes that the power-law hemolysis model employed is the de facto standard in the field, supported by over four decades of published application and endorsed in FDA guidance documents. The k-ω SST turbulence closure has been validated by the assessment team across three prior rotating machinery geometries. The Monte Carlo sensitivity analysis demonstrates that even at the upper bound of power-law exponent uncertainty, predicted NIH remains below the clinical threshold with a 1.8× margin. Two independent domain experts with combined experience exceeding 30 years reviewed the model form selection and provided written concurrence. While the panel acknowledges that a formal cross-geometry independent validation dataset was not assembled — which would have formally elevated Model form to level 4 — the totality of indirect evidence, the conservative safety margin, and the expert concurrence collectively provide confidence that model form uncertainty will not alter the regulatory decision. The panel therefore accepts the submission on the basis that the structural gap in Model form credibility is adequately compensated by the weight of contextual and experiential evidence, and that the risk of an incorrect hemolysis prediction leading to patient harm is sufficiently mitigated by the conservative clinical threshold margin.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
